photo.description: Liber Monast. b. M. V. in Rhino[uia?/wa?]. 1609. [17th-century ms. ownership inscription of Kloster Rheinau, a Benedictine abbey on the island of Rheinau in Switzerland under the patronage of the Blessed Virgin Mary and St. Fintan of Rheinau. The abbey was founded ca. 878 and suppressed in 1862 by the canton of Zurich, at which point a large part of its notable library passed to the Kantonsbibliothek (now Zentralbibliothek) Zurich (cf. this exhibition). The RBMS Latin Place Names file, following Graesse, gives Renaugia, Rhenaugia, Rhenovium, Ricnavia, Rignavia, Rinaugia, Rinauva, Rinowa, and Rivova for Rheinau, but I'm really not certain what the back end of this inscription is trying to express. Elsewhere in this volume (though not yet pictured) are the inscriptions "Liber Monasterij Rhenouiensis." and "S. Findani D: Tutelaris monast. Rhenaugiensis. M.DC[...] XXIV. Feb[...]", however, which make the identification with Kloster Rheinau pretty certain.] Penn Libraries call number: GC55 C6856 603c All images from this book
photo.title: 17th-century ms. ownership inscription of Kloster Rheinau, a Benedictine abbey on the island of Rheinau in Switzerland

photo.description: BIBLIOTHECK ST. ST. JOANNEUMS [Stamp of the library of the Joanneum in Graz, Austria, which was founded in 1811 by Archduke John of Austria (1782-1859) as a museum and educational institution. The latter was split off in the late 19th century to become the Technische Universität Graz, while the former became the Landesmuseum Joanneum (renamed the Universalmuseum Joanneum in 2009). The library has no established heading. The Joanneum and its various components have a ton of them. A note in the record for the "Steiermärkisches Landesmuseum Joanneum" (covering the institution from 1887-2009) reads: "The following headings for earlier names are valid AACR2 headings: Joanneum; Steiermärkisch-Ständisches Joanneum zu Graz; Steiermärkisch-Landschaftliches Joanneum zu Graz; Steiermärkisches Landesmuseum in Graz". photo.description: Likely Le Gendre Pierce Starkie (1796-1819) of Huntroyd (Lancashire, United Kingdom) or perhaps his father of the same name (1760-1807). This website on the Starkie family gives "Le Gendre Piers Starkie" for the elder (1760-1807) and "Le Gendre Pierce Starkie" for the younger (1796-1819). The book in which this plate appears (Abraham and Gottfried Bucholzer's Index Chronologicus) was purchased by the Penn Libraries in 1962, the same year the library of Guy Piers Le Gendre Starkie was sold by Sotheby's. At this sale the Huntington Library purchased a 14th-century Mariale ms. with the "[b]ookplate of Le Gendre Pierce Starkie (b. 1796)" that is known to have been owned by Richard Wroe. Penn's Index Chronologicus has Richard Wroe's autograph on the title leaf as well as this Starkie bookplate. This plate is therefore most likely that of Starkie the younger. Penn Libraries call number: GC55 B8537 584c 1599 All images from this book

photo.description: Woodcut arms probably to be associated with the principality of Braunschweig-Lüneburg-Wolffenbüttel. The work in which it appears contains a "Fürstliche Braunschweigische Hoffgerichts Ordnung"; various elements of the whole are present in the arms of Braunschweig-Lüneburg, and Wolffenbüttel. The initials "G.V.M.G." at head stand for "Gottes Versehen muss geschehen" ("God's providence must happen"), a motto which appears on (among other things) the coinage of Julius, Duke of Braunschweig-Lüneburg (1528-1589). Cf. this coin from Julius's reign, which includes the above arms on its reverse. Used by Conrad Horn of Wolfenbüttel. Blazon for the crest: Out of a Ducal Coronet a pillar proper, the top adorned with a Coronet and Plume of three Peacock’s Feathyers proper, charged with a Star argent; on either side of the Pillar, out of the Coronet, a Sickle argent, handles gules, the backs adorned with small tufts of Peacocks Feathers, and between the sickles before the pillar a Horse current argent. Established heading: Horn, Conrad, fl. 1565-1603 Penn Libraries call number: GC55 B8385L 571h All images from this book

photo.description: Autograph of Rob[er]t Finney, 1774 This book also has the following presentation inscription on front free endpaper: J[oh]n Finney; To His Son: Robert Finney; wisheth Health New Castle Jan. 1754. Dr. John Finney is the son of Robert Finney who emigrated from Ireland to Chester County, PA circa 1725. Robert Finney is the son of Dr. John Finney and Elizabeth Finney. Cf. this history in the Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography. Dr. John Finney had a very successful medical practice and owned a significant quantity of land and real estate in New Castle, DE, as well as Chester County, PA. This book also bears the autograph on the title page and p. 1 of David French, who was Elizabeth Finney's brother. Robert Finney has signed his name on p. [8], dated 1774. Penn Libraries call number: EC7 Ar195 731e 1735 All images from this book

photo.description: Probably Austin Lamont (1905-1969), son of Thomas W. Lamont, banker at JP Morgan after whom Harvard's Lamont Library is named. According to this article in Anesthesiology, Austin Lamont was "originally planning to study classic Latin and Greek at the New College, Oxford University, England, [but] he changed his mind while still on the steamship headed for Europe." He instead studied science and became a doctor and professor of anesthesiology at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine (1947-mid1960s). Austin and his 2nd wife Bodine were Philadelphia elites and associated with other prominent Philadelphians Carl and Laura Zigrosser. Carl Zigrosser was a prints curator at the Philadelphia Museum of Art and member of the Print Club (Philadelphia). A finding aid to Zigrosser's papers is available here. Other examples of Austin Lamont's autograph. Penn Libraries call number: EC7 Ad214 713c 1756
photo.title: Austin Lamont (1905-1969)

photo.description: Book label of John Penington & Son bookshop at 127 S. 7th Street in Philadelphia, PA. The Peningtons arrived in Pennsylvania in 1698 and were a leading and active Quaker family in Philadelphia business and politics. John Penington (1799-1867‏) and his son, Edward Penington, ran the book shop and specialized in rare and foreign books. John's father, Edward, was a bibliophile with a large personal library of over 6,000 volumes and was a prominent businessman in the city as a sugar refiner and merchant. Cf. the Penington Family Papers at the Historical Society of Pennsylvania. Established heading: John Penington & Son Established heading: Penington, John, 1799-1867 Penn Libraries call number: EC7 Ad214 705r 1761

photo.description: Bibliotheca August[...?] Angiae[?] [For Angia, Graesse gives Enghien, Hainaut, Belgium (home of a notable Jesuit library looted by the Nazis) and its namesake, the French commune Enghien-les-Bains north of Paris. In addition, the French duchy of Montmorency was renamed the Duchy of Enghien from 1689 until the Revolution. The commune of Montmorency, founded during the Revolution, was renamed Enghien in 1815; Montmorency persisted in rather confusing parallel usage until 1832, when it formally and finally replaced Enghien. Provenance indications for the Jesuit residence at Enghien, Belgium, include a bookplate ("Bibliotheca S.J. Maison Saint-Augustin Enghien") and stamp ("Collegium Angiense Societatis Jesu"). Cf. this book.] Penn Libraries call number: Inc C-66.5 All images from this book

photo.description: Bibliotheca August[...?] Angiae[?] [For Angia, Graesse gives Enghien, Hainaut, Belgium (home of a notable Jesuit library looted by the Nazis) and its namesake, the French commune Enghien-les-Bains north of Paris. In addition, the French duchy of Montmorency was renamed the Duchy of Enghien from 1689 until the Revolution. The commune of Montmorency, founded during the Revolution, was renamed Enghien in 1815; Montmorency persisted in rather confusing parallel usage until 1832, when it formally and finally replaced Enghien. Provenance indications for the Jesuit residence at Enghien, Belgium, include a bookplate ("Bibliotheca S.J. Maison Saint-Augustin Enghien") and stamp ("Collegium Angiense Societatis Jesu"). Cf. this book.] Woodcut printer's device of Antoine Caillaut of Paris. "The figure here is that of St. Anthony, the patron saint of the printer. The saint stands in front of his desert cell, holding a book and a rosary in one hand and his staff in the other. Behind him is a pig wearing a bell, a symbol of St. Anthony. The border contains the name of St. Anthony at the top and that of the printer on either side, his forename, Antoine, being part of the woodblock and his last name, Caillaut, being set in type. The two initial Cs are of different fonts."--M. Harman, Printer's and publisher's devices in incunabula in the University of Illinois Library, no. 17. Established heading: Caillaut, Antoine, active 1483-1506 Penn Libraries call number: Inc C-66.5 All images from this book

photo.description: Woodcut publisher's device (73 x 53 mm., hand-colored by a reader in green and red[?]) of Durand Gerlier of Paris on title leaf. "It is a rebus composed of a curry comb (étrille), a scythe (faux), and a calf (veau), for the address of Gerlier's shop, 'à l'Étrille-Fauveau.' The shield, which also contains the publisher's monogram, g g, is suspended from an oak tree and is supported on either side by a ram. Gerlier's full name is added at the foot of the device. (Meyer 96; Renouard 361; Polain 106; Silvestre 18; Veyrin-Torres, p. 410)"--M. Harman, Printer's and publisher's devices in incunabula in the University of Illinois Library, no. 19. Established form: Gerlier, Durand, ‡d fl. 1489-1529 Penn Libraries call number: Inc B-1201 All images from this book

photo.description: Arms of Albrecht von Brandenburg-Ansbach, subsequently Duke of Prussia. Used by Georg Osterberger of Königsberg [i.e. Kaliningrad]. One of 34 woodcut illustrations, each hand-colored, of the coats of arms of the Hochmeister or Grand Masters of the Teutonic Knights, a German Catholic military (and initially hospitaller) order founded in the 12th century. The Teutonic Knights ruled Prussia (the subject of the volume in which these illustrations appear) from the 13th century until 1525 when their Hochmeister Albrecht von Brandenburg-Ansbach converted to Lutheranism, secularized the territory and became the first Duke of Prussia.
